  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Subtask breakdown is the process of decomposing a complex goal into a set of smaller, independently executable subtasks with explicit dependencies. Well-structured decomposition makes complex tasks tractable for LLM agents: each subtask fits in context, can be verified individually, and can be parallelised when dependencies allow."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Hierarchical task decomposition: root task splits into subtasks A, B, C; each splits into atomic leaf subtasks; B.1 must complete before B.2 (dependency edge)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Decompose Tasks?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Context window limits: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "A complex task requiring 50+ tool calls and long intermediate outputs exceeds what fits in one context. Each subtask can be executed in its own focused context with only the relevant prior results passed in."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Parallelisation: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Independent subtasks run concurrently, reducing wall-clock time proportionally to the degree of parallelism."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Verifiability: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Each subtask has a clear completion criterion. If a subtask fails, the failure is localised and the correct prefix of work is preserved."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Specialisation: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Different subtasks can use different prompts, tools, models, or agents optimised for that step type (e.g. a retrieval agent for research, a code agent for implementation)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Re-planning: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If a subtask fails unexpectedly, only the downstream subtasks need re-planning, not the entire task."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LLM-Generated Decomposition"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest approach: ask the model to decompose the goal and return a structured list of subtasks with dependency edges. The model produces a flat DAG \u2014 no nesting \u2014 which is easier to execute than a tree:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import anthropic, json, re\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\n\nclient = anthropic.Anthropic()\n\nDECOMPOSE_PROMPT = \"\"\"Break the following task into 3-7 concrete subtasks.\nEach subtask must be independently executable by an AI agent.\n\nTask: {task}\n\nReturn ONLY a JSON array of subtask objects:\n[{{\"id\": \"t1\", \"title\": \"...\", \"description\": \"...\", \"depends_on\": []}}, ...]\n\nRules:\n- \"id\" is a short string like t1, t2, t3\n- \"depends_on\" lists ids that must complete before this subtask can start\n- Every leaf subtask must have a clear, verifiable completion criterion\n- Do not nest subtasks; keep the list flat with dependency edges\nNo markdown, no extra text.\"\"\"\n\n@dataclass\nclass Subtask:\n    id: str\n    title: str\n    description: str\n    depends_on: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n    result: str | None = None\n    status: str = \"pending\"  # pending | running | done | failed\n\ndef decompose_task(task: str) -> list[Subtask]:\n    raw = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n        max_tokens=2048,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": DECOMPOSE_PROMPT.format(task=task)}],\n    ).content[0].text\n    clean = re.sub(r\"^```[a-z]*\\n|```$\", \"\", raw.strip(), flags=re.M).strip()\n    data = json.loads(clean)\n    return [Subtask(**item) for item in data]\n\nsubtasks = decompose_task(\n    \"Build a REST API that accepts a GitHub repo URL, clones it, \"\n    \"runs the tests, and returns a summary of results.\"\n)\nfor s in subtasks:\n    deps = f\" (after {s.depends_on})\" if s.depends_on else \"\"\n    print(f\"[{s.id}]{deps} {s.title}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Dependency-Aware Execution Order"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A dependency DAG defines which subtasks can run in parallel. Topological sort groups them into waves: all tasks in a wave have their dependencies satisfied and can run concurrently; each wave waits for the previous to finish:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def topological_order(subtasks: list[Subtask]) -> list[list[Subtask]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Return subtasks grouped into waves.\n    All tasks in a wave can run in parallel; each wave waits for the previous.\n    \"\"\"\n    id_to_task = {s.id: s for s in subtasks}\n    remaining = set(s.id for s in subtasks)\n    completed = set()\n    waves = []\n\n    while remaining:\n        # Find all tasks whose dependencies are satisfied\n        ready = [\n            id_to_task[sid] for sid in remaining\n            if all(dep in completed for dep in id_to_task[sid].depends_on)\n        ]\n        if not ready:\n            raise ValueError(f\"Cycle detected in subtask dependencies: {remaining}\")\n        waves.append(ready)\n        for task in ready:\n            remaining.discard(task.id)\n            completed.add(task.id)\n    return waves\n\nwaves = topological_order(subtasks)\nfor i, wave in enumerate(waves):\n    print(f\"Wave {i+1} (parallel): {[s.title for s in wave]}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Parallel Execution with Context Passing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each subtask receives the goal and the results of the subtasks it depends on as context. Subtasks in the same wave run in parallel via ThreadPoolExecutor, since they are I/O-bound API calls:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor\n\nEXECUTE_PROMPT = \"\"\"You are an AI agent executing one step of a larger task.\n\nOverall goal: {goal}\n\nYour subtask:\nTitle: {title}\nDescription: {description}\n\nContext from prior steps:\n{prior_context}\n\nExecute this subtask and return your result. Be concise and precise.\nYour output will be passed as context to dependent subtasks.\"\"\"\n\ndef execute_subtask(subtask: Subtask, goal: str, completed: dict[str, str]) -> str:\n    prior = \"\\n\".join(\n        f\"[{sid}] {result}\"\n        for sid, result in completed.items()\n        if sid in subtask.depends_on\n    ) or \"None\"\n    return client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n        max_tokens=2048,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": EXECUTE_PROMPT.format(\n            goal=goal,\n            title=subtask.title,\n            description=subtask.description,\n            prior_context=prior,\n        )}],\n    ).content[0].text\n\ndef run_decomposed_task(goal: str) -> dict[str, str]:\n    subtasks = decompose_task(goal)\n    waves    = topological_order(subtasks)\n    results: dict[str, str] = {}\n\n    for wave in waves:\n        with ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=len(wave)) as pool:\n            wave_results = pool.map(\n                lambda s: (s.id, execute_subtask(s, goal, results)),\n                wave,\n            )\n        for sid, result in wave_results:\n            results[sid] = result\n            print(f\"  [{sid}] done ({len(result)} chars)\")\n\n    return results\n\nall_results = run_decomposed_task(\n    \"Write a technical blog post explaining how Python's GIL works \"\n    \"and when it matters for performance.\"\n)\nprint(\"Final output:\", list(all_results.values())[-1][:300])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Subtask Validation and Retry"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "After each subtask executes, a lightweight LLM check verifies whether the result actually satisfies the subtask's requirement. If not, the subtask is retried with failure context appended to the description:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def validate_subtask_result(\n    subtask: Subtask,\n    result: str,\n    goal: str,\n) -> tuple[bool, str]:\n    \"\"\"Ask an LLM to check whether the subtask result meets the goal.\"\"\"\n    verdict = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n        max_tokens=256,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": (\n            f\"Overall goal: {goal}\\n\"\n            f\"Subtask: {subtask.title} \u2014 {subtask.description}\\n\"\n            f\"Result:\\n{result[:1000]}\\n\\n\"\n            \"Does this result successfully complete the subtask? \"\n            \"Reply with YES or NO, then one sentence of reasoning.\"\n        )}],\n    ).content[0].text.strip()\n    ok = verdict.upper().startswith(\"YES\")\n    return ok, verdict\n\ndef run_with_validation(\n    goal: str,\n    max_retries: int = 2,\n) -> dict[str, str]:\n    subtasks = decompose_task(goal)\n    waves    = topological_order(subtasks)\n    results: dict[str, str] = {}\n\n    for wave in waves:\n        for subtask in wave:   # sequential within wave for simplicity here\n            for attempt in range(max_retries + 1):\n                result = execute_subtask(subtask, goal, results)\n                ok, reason = validate_subtask_result(subtask, result, goal)\n                if ok:\n                    results[subtask.id] = result\n                    break\n                if attempt == max_retries:\n                    raise RuntimeError(\n                        f\"Subtask {subtask.id} failed after {max_retries} retries: {reason}\"\n                    )\n                # Retry with failure context\n                subtask.description += f\"\\n\\nPrevious attempt failed: {reason}\"\n    return results"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Dynamic Re-Decomposition on Failure"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When a subtask fails irrecoverably (all retries exhausted), the remaining plan may be invalid. Re-decomposition asks the model to produce a revised set of subtasks starting from the failure point, preserving all completed work:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "REDECOMPOSE_PROMPT = \"\"\"A subtask in a larger plan has failed.\nSuggest a revised decomposition of the remaining work.\n\nOriginal goal: {goal}\nCompleted subtasks: {completed}\nFailed subtask: {failed_title} \u2014 {failed_desc}\nFailure reason: {reason}\n\nReturn a JSON array of new subtasks to replace the failed one and anything that depended on it.\nUse the same schema as before. Preserve completed work (do not re-do it).\nNo markdown, no extra text.\"\"\"\n\ndef redecompose_on_failure(\n    goal: str,\n    completed: dict[str, str],\n    failed_subtask: Subtask,\n    reason: str,\n) -> list[Subtask]:\n    raw = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n        max_tokens=2048,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": REDECOMPOSE_PROMPT.format(\n            goal=goal,\n            completed=list(completed.keys()),\n            failed_title=failed_subtask.title,\n            failed_desc=failed_subtask.description,\n            reason=reason,\n        )}],\n    ).content[0].text\n    import re\n    clean = re.sub(r\"^```[a-z]*\\n|```$\", \"\", raw.strip(), flags=re.M).strip()\n    data = json.loads(clean)\n    return [Subtask(**item) for item in data]"
          }
        ]
      },
